BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 790.00 Tm (5.3 The Key Concept: Roles, Not Passwords) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 771.84 Tm (On your laptop, you probably ran aws configure and pasted an access key.) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 755.98 Tm (That is a static credential. Like writing a password on a sticky note.) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 740.12 Tm (On AWS, the correct approach is:) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 720.26 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 708.38 Tm (Local dev:     AWS access keys in ~/.aws/credentials \(acceptable for dev\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 696.50 Tm (EC2 in prod:   IAM Instance Role \(no keys stored anywhere\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 684.62 Tm (ECS in prod:   IAM Task Role \(no keys stored anywhere\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 672.74 Tm (EKS in prod:   IRSA / Pod Identity \(no keys stored anywhere\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 660.86 Tm (Lambda:        Execution Role \(no keys stored anywhere\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 642.98 Tm (The application never sees or stores AWS credentials. AWS injects temporary credentials) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 629.12 Tm (automatically through the role.) Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 607.26 Tm (5.4 How It Actually Works for Your Spring Boot App) Tj ET
BT /F2 11.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 583.10 Tm (On EC2) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 562.92 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 551.04 Tm (1. You create an IAM role: myapp-backend-role) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 539.16 Tm (2. You attach policies to it:) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 527.28 Tm (     - s3:GetObject on the uploads bucket) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 515.40 Tm (     - secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on the DB password secret) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 503.52 Tm (     - sqs:SendMessage on the orders queue) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 491.64 Tm (3. You attach this role to the EC2 instance) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 479.76 Tm (4. Spring Boot uses the AWS SDK) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 467.88 Tm (5. The SDK automatically finds the role credentials via instance metadata) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 456.00 Tm (6. No access keys anywhere in your code or config) Tj ET
BT /F2 11.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 432.12 Tm (On ECS) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 411.94 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 400.06 Tm (1. You create an IAM Task Role: myapp-backend-task-role) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 388.18 Tm (2. Same policy attachments as above) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 376.30 Tm (3. You put the role ARN in the ECS task definition) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 364.42 Tm (4. Each running task gets its own temporary credentials) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 352.54 Tm (5. Different services can have different task roles -> least privilege) Tj ET
BT /F2 11.50 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 328.66 Tm (On EKS) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 308.48 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 296.60 Tm (1. You create an IAM role: myapp-backend-role) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 284.72 Tm (2. You create a Kubernetes ServiceAccount annotated with the role ARN \(IRSA\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 272.84 Tm (3. Pods using that ServiceAccount automatically get temporary AWS credentials) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 260.96 Tm (4. Pod A \(needs S3\) gets a different role than Pod B \(needs DynamoDB\)) Tj ET
