BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 790.00 Tm (  3. Is the consumer polling? \(check consumer logs or Lambda invocations\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 778.12 Tm (  4. Is the message going to DLQ? \(check DLQ queue depth\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 766.24 Tm (  5. Is the visibility timeout too short? \(message reappears before processing finishes\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 754.36 Tm () Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 742.48 Tm (Something is slow but you don't know where?) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 730.60 Tm (  1. Check ALB target response time \(is the backend slow?\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 718.72 Tm (  2. Check RDS CPU and connections \(is the DB the bottleneck?\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 706.84 Tm (  3. Check SQS message age \(is the queue backing up?\)) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 694.96 Tm (  4. Enable X-Ray for request-level tracing) Tj ET
0.6 w 46.00 671.08 m 549.00 671.08 l S
BT /F2 15.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 641.08 Tm (15. Interview-Ready Answers) Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 613.28 Tm (15.1 "How do you decouple services in your architecture?") Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 591.12 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 579.24 Tm ("I use the SNS + SQS fan-out pattern. The producing service publishes an) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 567.36 Tm (event to an SNS topic. Each consuming service has its own SQS queue) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 555.48 Tm (subscribed to the topic. This way, consumers are independent - they scale,) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 543.60 Tm (retry, and fail without affecting each other. The producer is decoupled) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 531.72 Tm (from knowing who consumes the event.") Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 507.84 Tm (15.2 "When would you use EventBridge over SNS?") Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 485.68 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 473.80 Tm ("I use SNS when the fan-out is simple - every subscriber gets every message.) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 461.92 Tm (I use EventBridge when I need content-based routing - different events go) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 450.04 Tm (to different targets based on rules that inspect the event body. EventBridge) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 438.16 Tm (also integrates natively with AWS service events like EC2 state changes or) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 426.28 Tm (S3 notifications, which makes it stronger for infrastructure-level eventing.") Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 402.40 Tm (15.3 "Where does Lambda fit in your architecture?") Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 380.24 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 368.36 Tm ("I use Lambda for event-driven glue tasks: processing SQS messages, reacting) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 356.48 Tm (to S3 uploads, running scheduled cleanups, and lightweight integrations.) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 344.60 Tm (I do not use Lambda for the main Spring Boot API because JVM cold starts) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 332.72 Tm (are too slow for user-facing requests. The main API runs on ECS or EKS.") Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 308.84 Tm (15.4 "How do you handle a multi-step process that can fail?") Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 286.68 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 274.80 Tm ("I use Step Functions to orchestrate the workflow. Each step is a Lambda) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 262.92 Tm (or service integration. Step Functions handles retries, error branching,) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 251.04 Tm (and compensation logic. For example, in an order saga, if inventory) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 239.16 Tm (reservation fails after payment is charged, Step Functions runs the refund) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 227.28 Tm (step automatically. The state of the workflow is always visible and auditable.") Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 203.40 Tm (15.5 "How do you monitor your system?") Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 181.24 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 169.36 Tm ("I use CloudWatch for three things: metrics for system health \(CPU, latency,) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 157.48 Tm (error rate, queue depth\), logs for debugging \(application logs shipped from) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 145.60 Tm (ECS or Lambda\), and alarms for alerting \(5xx spike, DLQ messages, saturated) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 133.72 Tm (resources\). For distributed tracing across microservices, I add X-Ray.) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 121.84 Tm (I build a CloudWatch dashboard so the team can see the entire system's) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 109.96 Tm (health at a glance.") Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 86.08 Tm (15.6 "Why must SQS consumers be idempotent?") Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 63.92 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F1 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 479.00 24.00 Tm (Page 146 of 147) Tj ET
endstream
endobj
150 0 obj
<< /Length 4870 >>
stream
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 790.00 Tm ("Standard SQS guarantees at-least-once delivery, meaning a message can) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 778.12 Tm (arrive more than once. If My consumer processes a payment and gets the) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 766.24 Tm (same message twice, it would charge the user twice without idempotency.) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 754.36 Tm (So I store a processed message ID before executing the business logic) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 742.48 Tm (and check it on every invocation. If already processed, I skip.") Tj ET
0.6 w 46.00 718.60 m 549.00 718.60 l S
BT /F2 15.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 688.60 Tm (16. Quick Revision Sheet) Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 660.80 Tm (One-Line Mapping) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 638.64 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 626.76 Tm (SQS            = durable message queue for async processing) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 614.88 Tm (SNS            = pub/sub fan-out to multiple subscribers) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 603.00 Tm (EventBridge    = smart event router with content-based rules) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 591.12 Tm (Lambda         = serverless function triggered by events) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 579.24 Tm (Step Functions = workflow orchestrator for multi-step processes) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 567.36 Tm (CloudWatch     = metrics, logs, alarms, dashboards) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 555.48 Tm (X-Ray          = distributed request tracing) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 543.60 Tm (SES            = managed email sending) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 531.72 Tm (WAF            = web application firewall at L7) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 519.84 Tm (ACM            = free TLS certificates) Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 495.96 Tm (When to Use What) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 473.80 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 461.92 Tm ("I need to do something later"                -> SQS) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 450.04 Tm ("I need to tell many listeners at once"        -> SNS) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 438.16 Tm ("I need to route events by content"            -> EventBridge) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 426.28 Tm ("I need a short function to react to an event" -> Lambda) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 414.40 Tm ("I need a multi-step workflow with retries"    -> Step Functions) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 402.52 Tm ("I need to see what is happening"              -> CloudWatch) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 390.64 Tm ("I need to trace a request across services"    -> X-Ray) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 378.76 Tm ("I need to send email"                         -> SES) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 366.88 Tm ("I need to block attacks at the HTTP layer"    -> WAF) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 355.00 Tm ("I need TLS certificates"                      -> ACM) Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 331.12 Tm (The Key Patterns in One Place) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 308.96 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 297.08 Tm (Async background work:        Producer -> SQS -> Consumer) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 285.20 Tm (Fan-out to many consumers:    Producer -> SNS -> SQS  N -> Consumers) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 273.32 Tm (Content-based event routing:  Producer -> EventBridge -> Rules -> Targets) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 261.44 Tm (File processing on upload:    S3 event -> Lambda) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 249.56 Tm (Scheduled cron job:           EventBridge rule -> Lambda) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 237.68 Tm (Multi-step saga:              Step Functions -> Lambdas with retry/compensate) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 225.80 Tm (Full observability:           CloudWatch metrics + logs + alarms + X-Ray traces) Tj ET
BT /F2 13.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 46.00 201.92 Tm (Gold Standard Sentence) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 54.00 179.76 Tm ([text]) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 167.88 Tm ("I keep my API fast by doing only critical work synchronously and offloading) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 156.00 Tm (the rest to SQS queues. I use SNS for fan-out when multiple services need) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 144.12 Tm (the same event, EventBridge when routing depends on event content, Lambda) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 132.24 Tm (for short reactive tasks, and Step Functions when the process has multiple) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 120.36 Tm (steps that can fail independently. CloudWatch gives me metrics, logs, and) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 108.48 Tm (alarms so I know what is happening, and X-Ray traces requests across service) Tj ET
BT /F3 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 58.00 96.60 Tm (boundaries.") Tj ET
BT /F1 9.00 Tf 1 0 0 1 479.00 24.00 Tm (Page 147 of 147) Tj ET
endstream
